'''The Auschwitz Institute for Peace and Reconciliation''' (AIPR) is a non-profit organization devoted to [[genocide]] and mass atrocity prevention.<ref name="ApselVerdeja2013">{{cite book|author1=Joyce Apsel|author2=Ernesto Verdeja|title=Genocide Matters: Ongoing Issues and Emerging Perspectives|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FXCAAAAAQBAJ&pg=PT214|date=21 August 2013|publisher=Taylor & Francis|isbn=978-1-135-92020-3|pages=214–}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://auschwitz.org/en/education/iceah-general-information/partners|title=Partners / ICEAH – General Information / Education / Auschwitz-Birkenau|first=|last=www.auschwitz.org|publisher=}}</ref> The institute is best known for its [[Raphael Lemkin]] Seminar for Genocide Prevention held annually at the [[Auschwitz concentration camp]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cpj.org/blog/2012/06/defining-role-of-the-press-in-genocide-prevention.php|title=Defining role of the press in genocide prevention - Committee to Protect Journalists|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://hnmcp.law.harvard.edu/projects/auschwitz-institute-for-peace-and-reconciliation/|title=Auschwitz Institute for Peace and Reconciliation « Harvard Negotiation & Mediation Clinical Program|publisher=}}</ref><ref name="ForceDanforth2008">{{cite book|author1=Genocide Prevention Task Force|author2=John C. Danforth|title=Preventing genocide: a blueprint for U.S. policymakers|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=j_G3DqKoLQ4C|year=2008|publisher=American Academy of Diplomacy}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jewishpress.com/indepth/columns/museum-and-the-auschwitz-institute-for-peace-and-reconciliation-raphael-lemkin-seminar-series/2008/05/28/|title=Museum And The Auschwitz Institute For Peace And Reconciliation Raphael Lemkin Seminar SeriesThe Jewish Press - Shmuel Ben Eliezer - 23 Iyyar 5768 – May 28, 2008 - JewishPress.com|first=Shmuel Ben|last=Eliezer|publisher=}}</ref> and for serving as the technical secretariat of the Latin American Network for Genocide and Mass Atrocity Prevention.<ref name="Bellamy2014">{{cite book|author=Alex J. Bellamy|title=Responsibility to Protect: A Defense|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KEKZBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA88|date=2 October 2014|publisher=OUP Oxford|isbn=978-0-19-100924-2|pages=88–}}</ref>
AIPR is an [[NGO]] that provides technical assistance and training to governments, emphasizing a long term approach to [[genocide prevention]]. It was founded in 2006<ref name="ApselVerdeja2013"/> by Fred Schwartz,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnlg.gov.rw/news-details/?tx_ttnews%5Btt_news%5D=149&cHash=d7015f853923c16dd28dcb4eeb9a40fb#.WOriwI61sUE|title=Founder of the Auschwitz Institute for peace and Reconciliation visits CNLG|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jta.org/2016/08/10/news-opinion/united-states/fred-the-furrier-schwartz-driver-of-auschwitz-shul-restoration-dies-at-83|title=Fred ‘the Furrier’ Schwartz, driver of Auschwitz shul restoration, dies at 83|date=10 August 2016|publisher=}}</ref> and is directed from its beginnings by Dr. Tibi Galis.<ref>[http://m.huffpost.com/us/entry/854010 ''Huffington Post'' website], accessed June 6, 2015</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.cuit.columbia.edu/rightsviews/2013/08/01/not-just-a-slogan-an-interview-with-tibi-galis-executive-director-of-the-auschwitz-institute-for-peace-and-reconciliation-on-genocide-prevention/|title=“Not Just a Slogan:” An Interview with Tibi Galis, Executive Director of the Auschwitz Institute for Peace and Reconciliation, on Genocide Prevention :: RightsViews|publisher=}}</ref> The organization has offices in [[New York City]]; in [[Buenos Aires, Argentina]]; in [[Kampala, Uganda]]; and in [[Oświęcim, Poland|Oswiecim, Poland]]. Its partner organizations include the [[United Nations]] Office on Genocide Prevention and the Responsibility to Protect<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.un.org/en/genocideprevention/partners.html|title=United Nations Office on Genocide Prevention and the Responsibility to Protect|first=United|last=Nations|publisher=}}</ref> and the [[Hague Institute for Global Justice]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehagueinstituteforglobaljustice.org/the-hague-approach/partners/|title=Partners – The Hague Institute for Global Justice|publisher=}}</ref>
